body: You will invariably get some differences between providers (it's impossible given the wide variety of computing hardware and operator implementations between various backends), that is more than I'd expect. Can you share a downloadable model? Then I could build with `ORT_DEBUG_NODE_IO_DUMP_OUTPUT_DATA` and compare at what point in the graph tensors really start to differ. Thanks.

@fdwr somehow github is rejecting attaching the model, but it can be found in the Pinto repository:
- Clone https://github.com/PINTO0309/PINTO_model_zoo
- Run 133_Real-ESRGAN\download.sh
- The model can be found with the name __realesrgan_256x256.onnx__
Thanks - found direct link in the .sh: https://drive.google.com/uc?export=download&id=1fIFXnvkm3vqxr0kGvKvPEcZq6ggHNgSL
@fdwr were you able to reproduce the problem?  just looking for a status report... no hurries.

I may have grabbed the wrong .onnx model (given the lack of description in Netron). How large was your file, about 18MB's? The download size is crazy at 8GBs!

[update] Finished downloading - have saved_model_256x256\realesrgan_256x256.onnx now, at 66'957'626 bytes.

[update] I get an assert trying to running it.
Program: ...d\x64-win-redist-debug\install\bin\onnxruntime.dll

Line: 275
Expression: transferredInitializerMap.empty()

Yes, `realesrgan_256x256.onnx` at a size of `66'957'626 bytes` is the file I'm using.

I'm running it from C# , and I don't get any assert, neither in CPU nor in DirectML

I'm not sure what's going on. My output image looks very blurry, for both CPU and DML :/ (good news is that neither looks any brighter/dimmer than the other): 
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1809166/142420558-ddfbde96-49c8-432a-ab9e-e3b5159f476e.png)

that's reeeeeeally weird.

Just in case we're using exactly the same file, the SHA256 of my `realesrgan_256x256.onnx` file is:

    86F3C4C530D0F739BA835D01E08343339CA2A18652A65E48649F53002A266717

Also, for inference `SessionOptions `on CPU, I'm using the default values, and for DML, I'm just calling `AppendExecutionProvider_DML` , no additional configuration used.

The input image is resized to match the 256x256 required size, and the RGB values normalized to floating values between 0 and 1

Also, remember I'm using onnxruntime 1,9 nugets, NOT the developement branch.

Other than that I think the model is quite straightforward

Ah, I didn't scale down to 0 to 1 earlier, and now it looks better (having the raw ONNX tensor .pb file after any preprocessing really helps rule out these differences between some models that take 0 to 255 directly vs others that need normalization first -_-).

Though, this is weird. If a run the graph with default optimizations, then I get a darker output. If I try to debug it though by finding where the first significant differences occur in the graph (by dumping out all the node tensors along the way to a directory full of .numpy tensor files and comparing them), then the difference no longer reproes 🤔, and both CPU and GPU look the same. So some transformation or fusion along the way is causing this.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1809166/142615393-3cd7f0b7-70bb-489f-b19c-202af423fb49.png)

Interesting... so some optimizations are messing the model...

And good to know you've been able to reproduce the issue.

So, this is a model issue, or there's a bug in the DirectML optimized path?
Seems so. It will be interesting to try ORT's GraphOptimizationLevel ORT_DISABLE_ALL to see if that makes a difference in the execution provider that calls DirectML...

@fdwr glad you're having some progress with the issue.

I only use OnnxRuntime from the C# side, so I'm not digging into de C++ code.

But, from what I undertand, when OnnxRuntime loads a model, it's able to optimize the graph if some conditions are met.

So, from the code you've written, my guess is that it's either `​ConvMulFusion::SatisfyCondition()​` that sometimes returns true when it should not.... or the fusion itself is wrong.

This issue has been automatically marked as stale due to inactivity and will be closed in 7 days if no further activity occurs. If further support is needed, please provide an update and/or more details.

I've tried with OnnxRuntime 1.11 and the issue is still present.

When I use the workaround `GraphOptimizationLevel = Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.GraphOptimizationLevel.ORT_DISABLE_ALL;` as suggested, the problem is resolved... 

But I am not sure if this workaround has been considered as the proper solution or if it remains a workaround until the underlaying issue has been resolved.
